TikTok hides objectionable videos from users
TikTok has over 500 million users worldwide, 40% of which are under 18.
Imagine China/Reuters
Chinese social networking site TikTok is censoring videos that mention Tiananmen Square, Tibetan independence, or the banned religious group Falun Gong.
The documents obtained by the publication reveal that the owner of TikTok, ByteDance, is using the app to promote Chinese foreign policy goals abroad.
The bulk of violations concerning Chinese policy fall under &quot;hate speech&quot;.
In each case, TikTok puts objectionable posts in a context that fits the general rules so that the actions of the social network do not look like censorship.
For example, the prohibition against criticizing China&#39;s socialist system falls under the general prohibition of &quot;criticizing or attacking the policies and social rules of any country, such as the constitutional monarchy, parliamentary system, etc.&quot;
The ban on mentioning the Tiananmen incidents or the Cambodian genocide falls under &quot;distortion of the history of China or other countries.&quot;
The document also lists the banned names of twenty &quot;foreign leaders or statesmen&quot;, including North Korean leaders Kim Jong Il, Kim Il Sung and Kim Jong Un, Indian politician Mahatma Gandhi, US Presidents Donald Trump and Barack Obama, Japanese Prime Minister Shinzo Abe, South Korean President Park Geun-hee, Indonesian President Joko Widodo and Indian Prime Minister Narendra Modi, the document says.
Prohibited material falls into two categories, the document says.
Publications from the first category are deleted by social network administrators and may result in blocking the user.
Not too severe violations fall into the second category: such posts remain on the site, but their distribution is limited by TikTok&#39;s algorithms.
ByteDance representatives told The Guardian that these rules are outdated and no longer apply: &quot;Now we use a localized approach for moderation, and also involve independent local specialists.&quot;
Russian TikTok users have no specific restrictions on publications, co-founder of the Producer Center Rustem Bogdanov says.
&quot;Producer Center&quot; is one of the Russian media companies that officially cooperates with TikTok.
All advertising materials of bloggers &quot;Producer Center&quot; coordinates with representatives of the social network, but user materials can be posted without approval, Bogdanov reports.
When asked whether it is possible to speak about politics or Putin on TikTok, Bogdanov answers in the affirmative and says that he has seen such publications.
Roman Zaripov, the founder of the Our Didgital agency, agrees with Bogdanov: “The basic rules for TikTok users are listed in the user agreement: you can’t post shocking content, discriminatory statements, and so on.”
But under these rules, you can bring any content that moderators do not like, Zaripov notes.
Zaripov&#39;s agency is another Russian TikTok partner.
According to TikTok, the number of its users in the world exceeds 500 million, 40% of which are under the age of 18.
According to the user agreement, only persons over the age of 13 can use TikTok.
Social network administrators check their age using artificial intelligence: a neural network analyzes faces and determines how old a person looks, says Bogdanov.
If the neural network decides that the user is younger, his account can be deleted, he adds.
According to RBC, in September 2019, ByteDance opened an office in Moscow on the territory of the WeWork coworking space.
