Deliveries of &quot;sanctions&quot; to Russia fell 100 times
The government of the Russian Federation has calculated that the supply of agricultural products and food to Russia from countries that fell under the Russian food embargo has decreased by more than 100 times since 2013.
According to the report sent to Russian President Vladimir Putin, in the first half of 2019, 31,000 tons of products were imported from the sanctioned countries against 3 million 442.2 thousand tons for the same period in 2013, Interfax reports.
At the same time, the cost of imported products decreased to $226.5 million from $4 billion 975.5 million, respectively.
We are talking about the supply of goods that did not fall under the embargo.
As indicated in the report, the dropped volumes of products prohibited for import were compensated for by increasing imports from the CIS countries, Africa, Southeast Asia, and Serbia.
Recall that at the end of August, the government extended until December 31, 2020 the validity of the rules for the destruction of agricultural products, raw materials and food, which are prohibited from being imported into Russia under counter-sanctions.
The document posted on the official portal of legal information noted that the validity of the rules was extended for another year - from December 31, 2019 to December 31, 2020.
Initially, the effect of the decision to destroy the sanction applied to products from the US, EU, Australia, Norway and Canada.
Later, from August 13, 2015, Albania, Montenegro, Iceland, Liechtenstein &quot;joined&quot; this list, from January 1, 2016 - Ukraine.
The decree signed by Putin on the destruction of illegally imported &quot;sanctions&quot; (products that fell under the food embargo that Moscow imposed in response to Western anti-Russian sanctions) entered into force in 2015.
In turn, the government allowed to destroy the &quot;sanctions&quot; food in any legal way.
As Western sanctions persist, Russia has also extended its retaliatory measures.
At the same time, this measure does not apply to products that citizens import for personal use.
The ban does not apply to the import of goods for personal consumption weighing up to 5 kilograms.
However, the head of the Council under the President of the Russian Federation for the development of civil society and human rights, Mikhail Fedotov, earlier called the destruction of food &quot;simply immoral&quot;, and this, according to him, negatively affects the education of people.
Moreover, the Rospotrebnadzor came up with the initiative to ban the destruction of food suitable for consumption in early June.
After that, a similar recommendation to the government was given by the Human Rights Council under the President of the Russian Federation.
And Deputy Prime Minister of the Russian Federation Alexei Gordeev said that it is wrong to destroy food, and we need to think about how to use them for their intended purpose, assessing the quality.
