Chile starts construction of €1bn telescope
This is reported by TASS with reference to the press service of the European Southern Observatory (ESO).
According to ESO, construction officially began this week on the dome of the building that will house the European Extremely Large Telescope (E-ELT), the most expensive and ambitious ground-based astronomical project so far.
Its total cost, according to ESO estimates, will exceed one billion euros.
Most of this money will be spent on the manufacture of equipment and the construction of the observatory building.
The most expensive and complex component of the telescope is its record-breaking large mirror, whose diameter will be about 39 meters.
It will be assembled from 798 hexagonal segments measuring 1.4 meters.
This huge mirror, as well as two auxiliary reflecting surfaces with a diameter of 4.2 and 3.75 meters, will help the E-ELT get the first detailed photographs of planets outside the solar system, stars in other galaxies, and also search for Earth&#39;s twins.
In addition, scientists will try to use this observatory to observe the vicinity of Sgr A*, the supermassive black hole at the center of the Milky Way.
Despite the fact that the construction of the dome has just begun, scientists, engineers and other specialists have been developing mirrors, scientific instruments and other components of the observatory for three years - since the announcement of the first plans for the construction of the E-ELT.
The contract for the production of the main mirror, whose total cost was about 400 million euros, was awarded to the German company SCHOTT and the French company Safran Reosc.
